Description: A co-stimulatory molecule highly expressed by T cells, as well as by other immune cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: 5T4 is an antagonist of the Beta-Catenin pathway.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: A protein highly expressed by melanoma cell, and it is also in the family of ABC transporter and P-glycoprotein family.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: A enzyme produced by the prostate and generally is elevated in men with prostate cancer.
A cell surface marker highly expressed in activated T cell.
Belongs to metallopeptidase family and help the maturation of TNF.
Belongs to metallopeptidase family.
It is a popular target in immuno-oncology due to its function of immunosuppressive effects in tumor microenvironment.
It is a popular target in immuno-oncology (not as prevalent as ADORA2A) due to its function of immunosuppressive effects in tumor microenvironment.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: A oncogene highly expressed by many cancer cell.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: A protein highly expressed in human fetus.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: This protein regulates the production of human milk.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Hormone receptor involved in male sex differentiation.
This protein is one type of angiopoietins, which induce apoptosis and formation of new vasculature.
This protein is one type of angiopoietins, which induce apoptosis and formation of new vasculature.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: The receptor of androgen hormone and it is highly expressed in certain types of prostate cancer.
In tumor microenvironment, arginase degrades arginine into urea. Arginine is an important amino acid for immune cell growth, and depletion of it lead to immunosuppression.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Overexpression of ASPH associates with increase incidence of cancer.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: This is a sodium-iodide transporter.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: AURKA is a kinase and its dysregulation is common among many cancer types. Its high expression among cancers make it a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: AURKB is a kinase and its dysregulation is common among many cancer types. Its high expression among cancers make it a target for cancer vaccine.
AXL receptor transduce signal from extracellular matrix in to cytoplasm
Binds to CD28, CTLA-4, or ICOS to induce subsequent signaling events mainly in immune cells.
Belongs to B7 family, which includes B7-H3. This molecule is reportedly a checkpoint molecule.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Belongs to B7 family and binds to NKp30.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: BAFF-R is member of TNF superfamily. It is highly expressed by certain lymphoma and is a target of cell therapy for this disease.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: BARD1 binds with BRCA1 to form a complex that stabilizes the function of BRCA1

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: BCL-2 is pro-apoptotic, which induces apoptosis.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: BCMA is specifically expressed on matured B cells. It is also a very popular target for CAR-T cells for multiple myeloma.
Beta-Catenin is an important component of Wnt/Beta-Catenin pathway, which plays critical role in many biological functions and diseases.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: BOB-1 is suggested to be a good marker for B-cell malignancies. CAR-T cell therapies against this target are being developed.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Brachyury is an important transcription factor that promotes epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT), and many cancer vaccines target this molecule.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Peptides derived from HSP90B1 are believed to be immunogenic in certain tumor environment and cancer vaccine are being developed based on those peptide sequences. Heat shock proteins are chaperon proteins that help other protein fold into the correct formation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Peptides derived from HSP90B1 are believed to be immunogenic in certain tumor environment and cancer vaccine are being developed based on those peptide sequences. Heat shock proteins are chaperon proteins that help other protein fold into the correct formation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: c-KIT is a cytokine receptor expressed on cell surface, and it plays role in many types of cancer and is a popular cancer target.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Carbonic anhydrases(CAs) are a large family of zinc metalloenzymes that catalyze the reversible hydration of carbon dioxide. It is overexpressed in certain solid tumors and it is a target for cancer vaccines.

CB2 is responsible for the cell proliferation of certain types of cancer cells. Small molecule that activate CB2 is reportedly to elevate the expression of MHC I on cancer cells, and this leads to enhanced immune response to the cancer cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CBL-B functions as a negative regulator of T-cell activation. CBL-B expression in T cells causes ligand-induced T cell receptor down-modulation, controlling the activation degree of T cells during antigen presentation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CCL20 is a strong chemokine that attracts lymphocytes.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CCL3 is a chemokine and it binds to CCR1, CCR4, and CCR5.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CCNB1 plays an important role in cell mitosis, especially during the G2 to M phase transition. It is highly expressed in certain cancers and is being pursued as a target for cancer vaccines.
CCR1 is a chemokine receptor that binds with CCL3, CCL5, CCL 7, and CCL23.

CCR2 is a chemokine receptor that binds with CCL2. CCR2 is important for monocyte migration into tumor or other inflammatory tissues. It is also important for monocytes to migrate out from bone marrow.
CCR4 is a chemokine receptor that binds with CCL2, CCL4, CCL7, CCL 17, and CCL22. It helps the migration of leukocytes.

CCR7 is a chemokine receptor that binds with CCL19 and CCL 21. CCR7 is highly expressed by certain types of dendritic cells, which play pivotal role in facilitate the anti-tumor adaptive immunity in cancer. CCR7 also plays role in T cell migration.
CCR9 is a chemokine receptor that binds to CCL25. CCR9 may play role in T cell migration in intestine and colon.
CD11b is a surface marker for leukocytes in the innate immune system, including monocytes, macrophages, granulocytes, and NK cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD123 is the receptor for IL-3, an important cytokine for the immune system. CD123 is highly expressed in acute myeloid leukemia, and is being pursued as a target for cancer cell therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD13 defects is associated with certain types of leukemia and lymphoma. CD13 is being pursued by cancer cell therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD133 is highly expressed in certain subtypes of melanoma cells. It is being pursed by several cancer vaccines as the target.
FLT3 is the receptor for FLT-3L. This pathway is important for normal hematopoietic stem cell development. It is also critical for B and T cell development. CD135 is a target for certain leukemia.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD138 is highly expressed in different tumor types and specifically on multiple myeloma cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD147 is highly expressed in certain immune cells and endothelial cells. CD147 is being pursued by cancer vaccines as a target.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD155 normally involves in the adhesion between epithelial cells and also involves in the poliovirus infection in primates.
CD16 has two isoforms, CD16a and CD16b. They are expressed in a wide range of immune cells and play important roles in phagocytosis and other key immune responses.
CD160's expression is strictly associated with peripheral blood NK cells and CD8 T lymphocytes with cytolytic effector activity. This molecule is a target for certain types of leukemia.
CD16a is one of the two isoforms of CD16. CD16a is expressed on mast cells, macrophages, and natural killer cells as a transmembrane receptor.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD171 is highly expressed in many types of cancer and its high expression is associated with poor prognosis.

Pathway: Glycosphingolipid biosynthesis - lacto and neolacto series
Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD174 is an enzyme encoded by human gene FUT3. It is highly expressed by certain types of blood malignancies and this molecule is a target for cancer cell therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD19 is expressed by B cells during all phases of their development. CD19 is an ideal target for cell therapy or monoclonal antibodies that are used for treating B-cell cancers.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD20 is expressed by B cells during all phases of their development except for the first and the last phases. CD20 is an ideal target for cell therapy or monoclonal antibodies that are used for treating B-cell cancers.
CD200 is expressed in myeloid cells such as macrophages. It is reported that the activation of CD200 may inhibit the activation of macrophages.
CD21 binds to iC3b, a key molecule in the complement system of the immune system.
CD22 functions as an inhibitory receptor forcell receptor (BCR) signaling. CD22 is also an important target for B-cell malignancies.

CD25 is the alpha chain of IL-2 receptor. Together with the beta chain, CD25 form the functional IL-2 receptor. The receptor binds to IL-2 and induce intracellular signaling that promote T cell proliferation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD267 is the receptor for ligands BAFF and APRIL. Activation of CD267 leads to the activation of NF-AT, NFkappaB, and AP-1.
CD27 is a co-stimulatory molecule of many immune cells. Activation of CD27 by its ligand CD70 leads to sustained T cell activation.

CD28 is a critical co-stimulatory molecule for T cell activation. Its binding ligands are CD80 and CD86. CD28 activation is an essential component for many cancer immunotherapies, especially the CAR-T therapies.
CD29 is an important molecule for cell adhesion. Activation of CD29 also increase the migration of leukocytes.
CD3 is the major component of TCR, and its intracellular signaling domain triggers cascades of intracellular events that control T cell activation.
CD3 is the major component of TCR, and its intracellular signaling domain triggers cascades of intracellular events that control T cell activation.
CD3 is the major component of TCR, and its intracellular signaling domain triggers cascades of intracellular events that control T cell activation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD30 is highly expressed by certain types of lymphoma and is being pursed as a target for those cancers.
CD32 is part of the B-cell co-receptors.
CD32 is part of the B-cell co-receptors.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD33 is generally expressed in myeloid cells. CD33 is a target for leukemia.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD38 is highly expressed in many types of immune cells. CD38 also functions in cell adhesion, signal transduction and calcium signaling.
CD39 is the enzyme involved in the pathway that hydrolyses extracellular ATP and leads to the generation of immunosuppressive adenosine. ATP promotes immune cell-mediated killing of cancer cells.
CD3E is part of the CD3, which is the major component of T-cell receptor complex. TCR is the key molecule for T cell activation and it binds to MHC I or II molecules.
CD4 is an essential component of TCR complex. CD4 guides the TCR complex to binds with MHCII molecule from antigen presenting cells.
CD40 is a receptor and it binds to ligand CD154. Activation of CD40 by its ligand activates the immune cells, most of which are T helper cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD44 is marker for effector-memory T cell. It is also widely expressed in wide range of immune cells. It is highly expressed in certain types of T-cell leukemia and therefore an ideal target for cancer cell therapy.
CD46 is a type I membrane protein and is a regulatory component of the complement system of the immune system.
CD47 is the receptor of SIRP, and the activation of CD47 by the binding of SIRP leads to the inhibition of phagocytosis process. This pathway is sometime referred to as "don't eat me" signal.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD51 is the essential subunit of integrins, which have different subtypes. CD51 is highly expressed in tumors such as colorectal cancer and prostate cancer.
CD52 is expressed by the mature lymphocytes but not their stem cell counterparts. It is a target for chronic lympholytic leukemia.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD54 is expressed on low level on leukocytes and endothelial cells, but its express is highly elevated when the cell are activated by infection or inflammation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD56 is highly expressed in NK cells, and its high expression is also associated with certain types of tumors.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD7 is highly expressed in certain types of T cell and it is a target for cell therapies.
CD70 is the ligand for CD27. CD70 activates CD27, which leads to the long-term maintenance of T cell immunity.
CD73 is an enzyme and it metabolizes AMP to produce adenosine, an immunosuppressive molecule that binds to adenosine 2A receptor.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD80 is a ligand for CD28 and CTLA-4, and it is expressed on antigen-presenting cells such as B-cells, macrophages, monocytes, and dendritic cells. The binding of CD80 to CD28 leads to T cell proliferation and serves as the essential co-stimulatory signal, or the secondary signal for T cell activation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD88 is the complement system receptor, whose binding to ligand C5a leads to strong inflammatory response.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CDH3 is a calcium-dependent cell-cell adhesion glycoprotein.
CDw136 has associative function with c-MET. CDw136 is shown to be interacted with Grb2

CEACAM1 is a member of CEA family and it is normally only expressed in cells at embryonic stage. However, certain cancers express this molecule at mature stages and therefore a target for cancer therapies.

CEACAM5 is a member of CEA family and it is normally only expressed in cells at embryonic stage. However, certain cancers express this molecule at mature stages and therefore a target for cancer therapies.

CEACAM6 is a member of CEA family and it is normally only expressed in cells at embryonic stage. However, certain cancers express this molecule at mature stages and therefore a target for cancer therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Claudin-18 belongs to claudin family, and it contributes to the formation of the tight junction strands in epithelial cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Claudin-6 belongs to claudin family, and it contributes to the formation of the tight junction strands in epithelial cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CLEC12A is highly expressed in acute myeloid leukemia cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: C-MET is a tyrosine kinase receptor, and its natural ligands are HGF and its spliced forms. High expression of c-MET associates with poor prognosis.
COX is an enzyme that produces prostanoids, which leads to inflammation and pain. Inhibition of COX relieve inflammation and pain.
COX-2 is one type of COX. COX is an enzyme that produces prostanoids, which leads to inflammation and pain. Inhibition of COX relieve inflammation and pain.
CPEG4 is highly expressed in cancer cells and therefore a target for cancer therapies such as oncolytic virus.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CRLF2 can forms a complex with TSLP and IL7R, and its engagement leads to the activation of JAK/STAT pathway as well as the cell proliferation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CS1 is highly expressed in multiple myeloma cells, and it is a target for cancer cell therapies and monoclonal antibodies.
CSF1 differentiates hematopoietic stem cells into the macrophages or other related cell types.

CSF1R is the receptor of CSF1, and the activation of CSF1R leads to the differentiation to macrophages and the survival of the cells too. CSF1R is highly expressed in tumor-associated macrophages, which take immunosuppressive role in tumors. Therefore, CSF1R is a popular target in immuno-oncology.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CTCFL is highly expressed in certain tumor cells and therefore is a target for cancer vaccines that are based on peptides derived from this protein.

CTLA-4 binds to CD80 or CD88 at much higher affinity than these two molecules binding to CD28. CTLA-4 therefore hijack the ligands from CD28, whose activation is essential for T cell activation and proliferation. CTLA-4 is a checkpoint molecule of T cells.
CX3CR1 is the receptor for CX3CL1. CX3CR1 involves in the adhesion and migration of leukocytes.
CXCL1 binds to CXCR2. CXCL is expressed by macrophages, neutrophils, and epithelial cells. It is also involved in renal cell carcinoma cell proliferation and therefore a target for this cancer.
CXCL12 is expressed in wide range of tissues, and it binds to CXCR4 and CXCR7. CXCL12 is a strong chemokine and its binding to CXCR4 leads to increased metastasis for certain tumor cells.
CXCL7 is involved in tumor migration and proliferation. Neutralization of this cytokine may prevent tumor growth.
CXCR1 is the receptor for IL-8, and its activation is important for neutrophil chemotaxis and activation. CXCR1 is highly expressed in certain malignant melanoma cells.
CXCR1 is the receptor for IL-8, and its activation is important for neutrophil chemotaxis and activation. CXCR2 also binds to CXCL1, CXCL2, CXCL3, and CXCL5.

CXCR4 binds to CXCL12, which is expressed in wide range of tissues. Blocking of CXCR4 leads to the release of hematopoietic stem cells release into the blood. Drugs antagonizing CXCR4 is being used to increase the blood levels of stem cells.

CXCR5 is the receptor of CXCL13, and its activation leads to the T cell migration into the B cell zone in the lymph nodes. Certain cancer cells rely on the signal from CXCR5 to proliferate and inhibition of this pathway prevent cancer growth.
CXCR7 is the receptor for chemokines CXCL11 and CXCL12.

Pathway: One carbon metabolism and related pathways
Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Cytosine deaminase that converts the prodrug (5 FC), co-administered along with these cells to the active cytotoxic agent (5 FU). This molecule is encoded by the stem cell therapy which migrate into tumor bed and convert pro-drug into chemotherapeutic agent.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: DCK is being utilized to convert gemcitabine prodrug to cytotoxic cancer therapy. DCK is being incorporated into oncolytic viruses that infect cancer cells and produce DCK to produce cytotoxic drugs in local tumor microenvironment.

EP300 functions as histone acetyltransferase that regulates transcription of genes via chromatin remodeling. This enzyme plays an essential role in regulating cell growth and division, prompting cells to mature and assume specialized functions (differentiate), and preventing the growth of cancerous tumors.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EGF is the ligand for EGFR. The binding of EGF to EGFR leads to the activation of this tyrosine kinase receptor pathway, leading to cell proliferation and growth.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EGFR is the receptor for EGF. The binding of EGF to EGFR leads to the activation of this tyrosine kinase receptor pathway, leading to cell proliferation and growth.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EGFR5 is highly expressed in tumor vasculature and is a target for cancer cell therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EGFRvIII is a translational variant of EGFR. It is highly expressed in glioblastoma and a few other tumors. EGFRvIII is an important target for cancer cell therapies against glioblastoma.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EIF2AK3 phosphorylates EIF2, and it is highly expressed in certain tumor cells. It is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: ELVAL4 is a RNA-binding protein. It is highly expressed in certain tumor cells and is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EPCAM is membrane protein and is highly expressed in certain types of tumors. It is a target for cancer vaccines and monoclonal antibodies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EPHA2 is highly expressed in certain cancer types and is a target for cancer cell therapies and CD3-targeted bispecific antibodies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EPSH8 is highly expressed in certain blood cancers and is a target for CAR-T therapy.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: ERG is highly expressed in certain cancer types and is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FAIM-3 is highly expressed by certain cancer types and is a target for cancer cell therapy.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FAP is highly expressed in human carcinomas. It is a target for cancer vaccines and oncolytic viruses.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FGF2 is the ligand for FGFR, and the association of the 2 molecules activates FGFR, which leads to cell proliferation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FN1 is a component of extracellular matrix and it binds to integrins from the cell. FN1 plays an important role in cell adhesion, growth, migration, and differentiation. Due to its high expression in cancer, FN1 is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: PSMA is an enzyme that is highly expressed in human prostate cancer. PSMA is a popular target for prostate cancer by various cancer therapy types.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FOLR1 is the receptor for folic acid. Many cancers highly express FLOR1 and it is a target for various cancer therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FOLR2 belongs to the folic acid receptor family. It has high affinity to folic acid and is highly expressed in many cancer types.

Pathway: Sudden Infant Death Syndrome (SIDS) Susceptibility Pathways
Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FOXM1 plays important role in cell cycle. Its upregulation was found in the majority of cancer types. Due to its high expression in cancer, it is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FSHR is highly expressed in ovary, testis, and uterus. It is a target for cancer cell therapy against ovarian cancer.
Galectin-1 induces the differentiation of dendritic cells towards a phenotype that educate the T cells to take an immunosuppressive phenotype. It is secreted by tumor cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Gastrin is a peptide hormone that induces the secretion of gastric acid (HCI). It is also highly expressed in gastric cancer and therefore a target for cancer vaccines for those cancers.
GCSFR is the receptor for GCSF. Engagement of GCSFR activates the downstream pathway that includes STAT and ERK1/2.
Galectin-3 plays important role in cell-cell adhesion, cell-matrix interaction, and macrophage activation. It is highly expressed in many types of cancer and is a target for various cancer therapies.
Galectin-9 is highly expressed in many blood malignancies and solid tumors, and therefore a target for therapies against this target.
GITR expression is elevated when T-cell is activated, and it is regarded as co-stimulatory molecule for T cells. It is a target for therapies to enhance T cell's functionality against tumors.
GMCSF is a cytokine and it induces the stem cells to produce granulocytes and monocytes. It is used to help the recovery of white blood cells after chemotherapy.
GMCSFR is the receptor for GMCSF, and activation of it leads to the production of white blood cell.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: The GnRHR is expressed on the surface of pituitary gonadotrope cells as well as lymphocytes, breast, ovary, and prostate. Due to its high expression in cancer of these organs, it is a target of cancer cell therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: GP73 is over-expressed in prostate cancer.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Gp96 is a chaperon protein that help the correct formation of proteins synthesized in cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: A cell membrane protein highly expressed by colon cancer cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: GPC3 is over expressed in liver cancer, ovarian cancer, and breast cancer.
The binding of glucocorticoids to GR leads to the expression of genes that lead to anti-inflammatory function. Antagonist of GR may reduce the immunosuppressive function of GR.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: H3.3K27M is mutant form of histone protein H3.3 with a point mutation of K to M at amino acid 27. It is suggested to be a good target for cancer vaccine as this point mutation is prevalent in certain types of pediatric glioma.
HDAC1 removes the acetylation of histones and therefore regulate the gene expression. It is reported that HDAC1 inhibitors may reduce the immunosuppressive phenotypes of certain immune cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Amplification of HER2 is a hallmark of HER2+ breast cancer. HER2 is also over expressed in many other cancer types and therefore an attractive target.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: HER3 is a tyrosine kinase receptor. Activation of HER3 leads to the activation of PI3K/Akt pathway. Due to its high expression in certain cancers, it is a target for cancer vaccines.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: HILPDA is over expressed in certain tumor due to the hypoxia. It is being pursued as a cancer vaccine target.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: HLA-A2 is a serotype of HLA-A.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: HMW-MAA is over expressed in melanoma cells and a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: HP59 is over expressed in tumor vasculature. It is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: HSP105 is over expressed in colorectal cancer and a target for cancer vaccines for this cancer.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: HSP70 is over expressed in human melanoma and non-small cell lung cancer. It is a caner vaccine target for those cancers.
HVEM is a cell membrane receptor and it is used by HSV to enter infected cells.
ICOS is a CD28 family member and works as a co-stimulatory molecule for T cells. It may preferentially activate Th2 cells. It is a popular target for T cells in immuno-oncology.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: IDH1 is a an enzyme, whose product plays important role for DNA modification and therefore gene expression. IDH1 mutation is associated with poor prognosis of certain cancers, especially glioblastoma. Recent studies suggest IDH1 modulating drugs may also affect immune cells' function against cancer growth.

IDO (encoded by IDO1 gene) is one the three enzymes that catalyze the first and rate-limiting step of in the kynurenine pathway. Kynurenine is a immunosuppressive molecule that binds to its receptor and induce immunosuppressive function on immune cells, especially T cell. Inhibiting IDO has been tested as a promising strategy to tackle the immunosuppressive microenvironment of tumors.
IDO2 is an enzyme with similar sequence and function to IDO but IDO2 has much narrower expression among tissues and much less enzymatic activities.
IFNAR1 is one of the two subunits of the receptor for type I interferons. The activation of the receptor leads to the activation of downstream signaling molecules through STAT1/2 pathway.
Interferon beta is the cytokine that binds to interferon receptor. It has 2 isoforms, interferon beta 1 and 2.
IFNAR2 is one of the two subunits of the receptor for type I interferons. The activation of the receptor leads to the activation of downstream signaling molecules through STAT1/2 pathway.
IFNGR1 is one of the two subunits of interferon-gamma receptor. The activation of the receptor leads to the activation of downstream JAK/STAT pathway that promotes inflammatory responses.
IFNGR2 is one of the two subunits of interferon-gamma receptor. The activation of the receptor leads to the activation of downstream JAK/STAT pathway that promotes inflammatory responses.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: IGF1 is a hormone that promotes cell growth. Its levels are elevated in certain tumors and reducing its levels is a target for cancer therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: IGF1R is the receptor for IGF1, and this hormone receptor promote the cancer cell growth and anti-apoptosis function. It is a target for cancer therapy.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: IGF2 is a hormone that promotes cell growth. It is also highly expressed in certain cancers and reducing its levels is a strategy for cancer therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: IGFBP2 is highly expressed in ovarian cancer cells and is a target for cancer vaccine.

IL-10 is traditionally believed to be an immunosuppressive cytokine that inhibits JAK/STAT pathway. Recent studies suggest IL-10 can also elevate the anti-tumor immunity through the interferon-gamma and CD8+ T cells.

IL10RA is a receptor for interleukin 10. This protein is structurally related to interferon receptors. It has been shown to mediate the immunosuppressive signal of interleukin 10, and thus inhibits the synthesis of proinflammatory cytokines.
IL12 is cytokine that help the differentiation of T cells to Th1 cells. It also have other functions to promote the growth of other immune cells.
IL12RB1 encodes the beta 1 subunit of IL12R. The two units together form the functional receptor and its activation leads to the downstream signal activation.

IL13 is reported to have similar function to IL-4. It mainly involves in immune response to parasite infection. However, recent studies show that extrinsic expression of IL-13 may enhance anti-tumor immunity.
IL13RA1 is the subunit of IL13 receptor.

IL13RA2 binds much stronger to IL13 than IL13 receptor itself, and it works as a negative regulator of IL13. It is highly expressed in certain tumors, especially in glioblastoma and therefore an attractive target.

IL15 is secreted by mononuclear phagocytes and its expression activates innate immunity against viral infection. The cytokine is reported to be involved in T-cell lymphoma and therefore a target for this disease.
IL17A is one subtype of IL17 cytokine and it induces a various of inflammatory responses.
IL17B is one subtype of IL17 cytokine and it induces a various of inflammatory responses.
Interleukin 1 beta is a cytokine that involves in autoimmune disease.
IL1R1 is the receptor for IL1 alpha and IL1 beta.
IL1R3 is an accessory protein to IL1 receptor.
IL21R is the receptor for cytokine IL21.
IL23R is the receptor for cytokine IL23. Engagement of IL23 leads to the activation of JAK/STAT pathway, which promotes immune cell activation and proliferation.
IL2RB is a subunit of IL-2 receptor.
IL36-gamma binds to its receptor and activate immune cell functions.

IL6 is secreted by T cells and macrophages and it induces immune responses. It is the major cytokine that is responsible for the cytokine release syndrome accompanying CAR-T therapies for blood cancer.
IL6R is the receptor for IL6.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: IL8 is the ligand for CXCR1 and CXCR2, and it is a chemokine that helps the migration of neutrophils. As neutrophils generally promote tumor growth, inhibition of IL8 may reduce neutrophil migration into tumor and therefore reduce tumor growth.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: IL9R is the receptor for IL9.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Integrin beta-7 is highly expressed by multiple myeloma cells and is a target for this disease.
IRAK1 is associated with IL-1 receptor and the binding of IL1 to IL1R leads to the activation of this kinase, which initiates subsequent signaling pathway within the cells.
IRAK4 is a protein kinase involves in toll-like receptors and T-cell receptor. IRAK4 involves in inflammatory disease and certain types of lymphoma.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: ITGB5 is over expressed in glioblastoma and therefore is a target for delivery of therapies that are designed to treat this disease.
JAK1 is a member of the JAK family. JAK1 interacts with the common gamma chain of type I cytokine receptors. JAK1 relies the signal from those receptors to the downstream signal molecules.

JAK2 is a member of the JAK family. JAK1 relies signal from the type II cytokine receptors, GM-CSF receptor family, and gp130 receptor family and the single-chain receptors. JAK2 relies the signal from those receptors to the downstream signal molecules.
JAK3 involves in the receptor signaling mediated by the common gamma chain of type I receptors.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: KIF20A was found to be highly expressed in pancreatic cancer and is a target of cancer vaccine for this cancer type.
KIR2DL1 is expressed by natural killer cells and certain subtypes of T cells, and its engagement leads to inhibitory signal downstream.
KIR2DL2 is expressed by natural killer cells and certain subtypes of T cell, and its engagement leads to inhibitory signal downstream.
KIR2DL3 is expressed by natural killer cells and certain subtypes of T cell, and its engagement leads to inhibitory signal downstream.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: KRAS is a member of the RAS family, and it plays essential role in many types of cancer. KRAS mutation is reported to be the driver gene mutation in a large number of cancer cases. Therapies against particular mutations of KRAS are being developed.

LAG-3 binds to MHCII, which is main binding partner of CD4. By hijacking MHCII from CD4, LAG-3 negatively regulate the activation of CD4+ T cell's TCR signaling pathway. LAG-3 is reported to help maintain CD8 T cell function too. LAG-3 is an immune checkpoint molecule.
LXRA and LXRB, two isoforms of LXR, are key regulator of macrophage function. Activation of LXR educate macrophages to adopt an anti-inflammatory phenotype.
LXRA and LXRB, two isoforms of LXR, are key regulator of macrophage function. Activation of LXR educate macrophages to adopt an anti-inflammatory phenotype.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MAGE-A1 is a member of the MAGE family and it is highly expressed in melanoma and a few other cancer types.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MAGE-A10 is a member of the MAGE family and it is highly expressed in melanoma and a few other cancer types.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MAGE-A3 is a member of the MAGE family and it is highly expressed in melanoma and a few other cancer types.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MAGE-A4 is a member of the MAGE family and it is highly expressed in melanoma and a few other cancer types.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MAGE-C2 is a member of the MAGEC gene family. It is not expressed in normal tissues, except for testis, and is expressed in tumors of various histological types.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Mammaglobin A is highly expressed by certain types of breast cancer and is a target for vaccine against this disease.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Mas receptor (MAS1) is a G-protein coupled receptor. Its ligands include adenine and 8-aminoadenine. It is a target of cancer vaccine.
MDA5 recognizes dsDNA and activate innate immune response. Activation of it is believed to enhance the anti-tumor immunity.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MDM2 is a negative regulator of P53 and it is highly expressed in many tumor types, which is a target for cancer vaccine.
MERTK is highly expressed in certain cancer cells and is a target for monoclonal antibody therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Mesothelin is highly expressed in mesothelial cells, and those cells line the pleura, peritoneum, and pericardium. Mesothelin is a target for mesothelioma and other cancer highly expressing this molecule.
MICB is related to MHC I and shares similar structure with MHC I. MICA is a stress-induced ligand for NKG2D and is broadly recognized by NK cells.
MIF is an inflammatory cytokine and it binds to CD74 and induces acute inflammatory responses.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MLANA is found on the surface of melanocytes. It is highly expressed by melanoma cells and therefore a target for this disease.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MMP-11 is a member of metalloproteinase family. MMP-11 degrades extracellular matrix. Due to its high expression in tumors, it is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MRP1 is a membrane transporter and it allows tumor cells to transport many chemotherapeutic compounds out of cancer cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MUC1 is a glycoprotein and it lines the apical surface of epithelial cells in many tissue. MUC1 is found to highly expressed in highly expressed in many solid tumors and is a target for cancer vaccines and cell therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MUC16 is biomarker for ovarian cancer due to its high expression. MUC16 is also a target for ovarian cancer.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MYB is a transcription factor. It is highly expressed in colorectal cancer and adenoid cystic carcinoma. It is a target of cancer vaccine against these cancers.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MYBL2 is a transcription factor and is highly expressed in certain tumor cells. Oncolytic virus has been designed to use MYBL2 as the transcription factor to promote the gene expression of oncolytic genes.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: N-Myc is a transcription factor and amplification of N-Myc leads to tumorigenesis. Peptides derived from N-Myc are being used as cancer vaccines.
NKG2A dimerizes with CD94 to form an inhibitory receptor on NK cell surface.
NKG2D forms a homodimer and serves as an activating receptor for NK cells.
NKp46 is a cell surface marker for NK cells.
NLRP3 is predominantly expressed by macrophages and it is a component of inflammasome. Activation of inflammasome through NLRP3 is believed to promote the anti-tumor immunity of macrophages.
NR2F5 is found to over expressed in leukemia, ovarian cancer, and endometrial cancer. Strategy to silence its expression in stem cell is being pursued as cancer treatment.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: NY-ESO-1 is found to highly expressed in melanoma with poor prognosis. It is also found to be highly expressed in many other solid tumors. It is a target for cancer vaccine and cell therapies.
OX40 is the receptor on T cells and it binds to OX40 ligand. Activation of this receptor improves the survival of activated T cells.
P2RX7 is found on microglia and macrophages. It plays a role in inflammatory response. Activation of this receptor may increase the anti-tumor immunity.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: P53 is a tumor suppressor and plays a pivotal role in controlling tumorigenesis. Cancer therapies are being developed to increase or restore the modified function of P53.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: PASD1 is highly expressed in various cancer types and is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: PBF is found to highly express in pituitary tumors and breast cancer. It is therefore used as a target for cancer vaccines in those tumors.

PD-1 is a immune checkpoint molecule and inhibition of it leads to the anti-tumor immunity of T cells. It is the most important target in cancer immunotherapy as of today and many therapies against it have been approved for cancer.

PD-L1 is the major ligand to PD-1 and it is highly expressed by cancer cells and other immune cells, especially macrophages and dendritic cells. Inhibiting PD-L1 is a viable method to unleash the anti-tumor immunity of T cells and a few drugs against this target have been approved.
PD-L2 is a ligand to PD-1. Its expression is not as wide as PD-L1 and its function in binding PD-1 is not very clear at the moment.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: PMEL is expressed in melanoma cells. It is a target for cancer vaccine against melanoma.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: POTE is highly expressed in testis and it is target for cancer of testis origin. It is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: PRAME is predominantly expressed in human melanoma cells but not in normal tissues, except for testis. It is a target for cancer vaccine and cell therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: PSA is secreted by the epithelial cells of prostate gland. PSA level is elevated in prostate cancer patients, and it is a diagnosis marker for this disease. PSA is also a target for cancer vaccines against prostate cancer.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: PSCA is a membrane protein that is highly expressed in prostate, kidney, colon, bladder, placenta, and stomach. It is a target of cell therapies for cancer of those tissue origins.

PVRIG is believed to be a immune checkpoint molecule, and PVRL2 is its ligand. Disruption of this association leads to enhanced T cell immunity against cancer cells and this inhibition increases T cell proliferation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: RhoC is GTPase and it is frequently mutated in cancers. Mutated RhoC is a target for cancer vaccines.
RIG-I is a pattern recognition receptor for viruses. Activation of it leads to inflammatory response and is a target for cancer immunotherapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: ROR1 is found to highly express in cancer stem cell and play a role in tumor migration and metastasis. It is a cell membrane receptor and therefore a target for cancer cell therapy.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: ROR2 is cell membrane receptor and promotes cell growth of certain cancer cells. It is a target for cancer cell therapies.

RORC is the gene that encodes ROR-gamma. ROR-gamma is an important nuclear receptor that plays important role in assisting CD4+ T cells to differentiating to Th17 cells. Th17 cells generate inflammatory cytokine and enhance anti-tumor immunity.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: The short form of SIM2, called SIM2s, has tumor suppressive properties. It is a target of cancer vaccine.

SIRPA is an inhibitory ligand that binds to CD47, the "do not eat me" receptor from phagocytes. Binding of SIRPA to CD47 prevents phagocytosis. Blocking of this ligand leads to increased phagocytosis of tumor cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: SOX is an transcription factor and it plays role in certain tumor types. It is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: SPAM1 degrades hyaluronic acid, a major structural proteoglycan found in extracellular matrices and basement membranes. SAPM1 as a hyaluronidase degrades extracellular matrix, which block the therapeutic effects of many cancer drugs. Strategies to increase hyaluronidase level are used to increase cancer drugs effectiveness.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: SSTR acts on many sites to inhibit the release of hormones and other secretory proteins. SSTR2 is also highly expressed in several cancer types and a target for cancer therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: SSX2 is highly expressed by synovial sarcoma cells. It is a target for cancer therapies.

STAT1 is member of STAT family and it generally responds to IFN-alpha, IFN-beta, IFN-gamma, EGF, PDGF, and IL-6. Small molecules to activate STAT1 are drug candidates to boost immune response against cancer.

STAT3 is member of STAT family and it generally responds to IFN-alpha, IFN-beta, IFN-gamma, EGF, PDGF, and IL-6. STAT3 is essential for the differentiation of Th17 cells, which generate inflammatory cytokines to promote anti-tumor immunity.

STING plays an important role in innate immunity. STING induces type I interferon production, which leads to activated innate immune response. Agonists against STING are being developed as cancer immunotherapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Survivin is a member of inhibitors of apoptosis (IAP) family and it allows cells to resist apoptosis. It is highly expressed in a few cancers, especially in breast cancer and lung cancer. It is a target for many cancer vaccines and a few cell therapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TASTD2 is a carcinoma-associated protein expressed on cancer cells. It is a target for CD3-targeted bispecific antibodies.

TDO is an enzyme that metabolizes tryptophan into kynurenine. Kynurenine is a signaling molecule that binds to immune cells and induce immunosuppressive function. Inhibition of TDO leads to enhanced anti-tumor immunity.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TERT prolongs the telomere of cancer cells and enhance their survival.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: This gene encodes a member of the DP family of transcription factors. These factors heterodimerize with E2F proteins to enhance their DNA-binding activity and promote transcription from E2F target genes. This protein functions as a negative regulator and inhibits the DNA binding and transcriptional activities of E2F factors. It is a target of cancer vaccine.
TGF-beta1 is one of the 4 isoforms of TGF-beta, and this molecule predominantly presents immunosuppressive functions on immune cells.
TGF-beta2 is one of the 4 isoforms of TGF-beta, and this molecule predominantly presents immunosuppressive functions on immune cells.

TGFBR1 forms the heterodimer complex of TGF receptor, which binds to TGF and leads to the activation of the pathway. Activation of TGF-beta receptor plays dominantly immunosuppressive role in the immune cells.

TGFBR2 is a transmembrane protein that has a protein kinase domain, forms a heterodimeric complex with TGF-beta receptor type-1, and binds TGF-beta. Activation of TGF-beta receptor plays dominantly immunosuppressive role in the immune cells.

TIGIT is immune checkpoint molecule and cell surface receptor. It is highly expressed on activated T cells. TIGIT binds to its ligands CD155 and CD112. Blocking the binding of ligands to TIGIT is promising strategies to enhance T cell's anti-tumor immunity.

TIM-3 is immune checkpoint and cell surface receptor. Its ligand is mainly Galectin 9. TIM-3 is highly expressed in tumor-infiltrating leukocytes. Blocking its binding with its ligand is pursued by many cancer immunotherapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TIMP3 is an inhibitor of matrix metalloproteinases. TIMP3 is incorporated into oncolytic virus as a product to prevent the degradation of extracellular matrix.
TLR2 is a membrane protein and it binds with lipid-containing pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs), such as lipoteichoic acid and di- and tri-acylated cysteine-containing lipopeptides.
TLR3 is a member of TLR family and it recognizes dsRNA. Its activation leads to innate immunity activation.
TLR4 is a surface receptor and binds to lipopolysaccharide (LPS). It is a member of TLR family and it activates innate immune responses.
TLR5 is a surface receptor and binds to bacterial flagellum. It is a member of TLR family and it activates innate immune responses.
TLR7 recognizes single-strand RNA in endosomes.
TLR8 recognizes GU-rich single-stranded RNA and G-rich oligonucleotides. It is endosomal receptor recognizing ssRNA too.
TLR9 recognizes CpG sequences in DNA molecules. TLR9 generally locates in endoplasmic reticulum.
TNF is cytokine and is involved in acute inflammation. It has wide range of functions on immune cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TOP1 is a DNA topoisomerase, an enzyme controlling the topologic states of DNA during transcription. Targeting this molecule is a strategy for stem cell therapy for cancer.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TRAIL is a ligand for death receptor 4 (DR4) and 5 (DR5). It also binds to DcR2, whose activation is believed to promote inflammation. Therefore, agonists similar to TRAIL are being evaluated as cancer immunotherapies.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TRP2 is over expressed by a variety of cancers, and it is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TSHR is a G protein-coupled receptor. It is the receptor of thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). It is found on the surface of thyroid epithelial cells. It is highly expressed on thyroid cancer and target for cancer therapies.
TWEAK is the ligand for TWEAK receptor (TWEAKR). This pair is believed to have pro-inflammatory function.
TYK2 is the first member of JAK family, along with JAK1, JAK2, and JAK3. Tyk2 can be activated by IL12 and type I interferon, as well as IL10.
TYRO3 is highly expressed in certain cancers and therefore a target for cancer therapy.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Tyrosinase is believed to be highly expressed by myeloid derived suppressor cells (MDSCs). It is a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: URLC10 is a tumor-associated antigen highly expressed in NSCLC. It is also a target for cancer vaccine.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: VEGFA exerts it primary functions through the interaction with VEGFR1 and 2. The activation of VEGFR1/2 by VEGFA also leads to macrophage migration.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: VEGFR1 binds to VEGFA and VEGFB, but its function is not well understood.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: VEGFR2 binds to VEGFA, VEGFC , and VEGFE. It is the main subtype of VEGFR molecule to relay the VEGFR signaling pathway.

VISTA is an immune checkpoint molecule. It is highly expressed in tumor infiltrating leukocytes. VISTA can be both a ligand and a receptor, and both functions lead to immunosuppressive phenotype on T cells.
VSIG-4 is expressed on macrophages, and it may interact with T cells and inhibit normal T cell anti-tumor functions.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: WT1 is the target for cancer vaccines and cell therapies as it is highly expressed in many types of cancers.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: ZP3 is highly expressed in some cancers but not in normal mature cells. It is a target for cancer vaccine.
ADORA3 is a GPCR involved in a variety of intracellular signaling.
ATM is a serine/threonine kinase involved in DNA double-strand break damage response.
ATR is a serine/threonine kinase involved in response to single strand DNA breaks.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: FMNL1 is implicated in morphogenesis, cytokinesis, and cell polarity.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Calreticulin binds misfolded protein and prevents export from the ER to the Golgi apparatus.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Caspase-9 is an initiator caspase in apoptotic pathway.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD1 proteins mediate the presentation of primarily lipid and glycolipid antigens of self or microbial origin to T cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD5 is expressed on T cell surface.
CD8 is a coreceptor of T cell receptor.
MIC3 or CD9 is a cell surface glycoprotein, known to complex with integrins and other transmembrane 4 superfamily proteins.
CD37 is expressed in highest abundance on mature B cells, and to a lesser extent on T cells and myeloid cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Cadherin17 is an adhesion molecule.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CAK1 or CDK7 mediates progression through the cell cycle.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Chorionic gonadotropin subunit beta 3 is a glycoprotein.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: C-C motif chemokine receptor 5 is cell surface protein on white blood cells that acts as a receptor for chemokines.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Claudin 3 is involved in tight junctions.
Mitogen-activated protein kinase 14 or p38 alpha is implicated in diverse cellular functions.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Cytochrome P450 family 1 subfamily B member 1 acts in drug metabolism and lipid synthesis.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD55 is a glycoprotein.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EMR1 is an adhesion GPCR.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: EPH receptor A3 is protein-tyrosine kinase implicated in development.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD23 is an antibody isotype involved in allergy and resistance to parasites, and important in regulating IgE levels.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD64 is a glycoprotein found on macrophages and monocytes.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Fibroblast growth factor 5 involved in different signaling cascades including PI3K, RAS-MAPK, and STAT.
GARP is a regulator of TGFB1, TGFB2, and TGFB3.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: GDNF or glial cell derived neurotrophic factor is secreted ligand of the TGF-beta superfamily of proteins.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Growth hormone releasing hormone triggers the release of growth hormone.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Gonadotropin releasing hormone 1 leads to the synthesis and secretion of gonadotropins LH and FSH.
CCR10 is a chemokine receptor and is involved in T cell-mediated skin inflammation.
CXCR3 or C-X-C motif chemokine receptor 3 is expressed on activated T lymphocytes and NK cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Guanylate cyclase 2C is a key receptor for heat-stable enterotoxins.
Histone deacetylase 2 removes acetyl groups from the lysine residues at the N-terminal of core histones.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CD168 or Hyaluronan mediated motility receptor is overexpressed in breast cancer.
Interleukin 1 alpha is produced by activated macrophages and can lead to the activation of tumor necrosis factor-alpha.
interleukin 4 induces nave helper T cells to differentiate.
interleukin 4 receptor binds its ligand to induce nave helper T cells to differentiate.
CD130 or interleukin 6 signal transducer is a subunit of IL6-receptor family.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Interleukin 18 induces interferon-gamma production and may modulate both innate and adaptive immunity.
integrin subunit alpha 4 is involved in lymphocyte migration.
Galectin 3 binding protein is elevated in the serum of some cancer patients and may be implicated in immune response associated with natural killer cells and lymphokine-activated killer cells.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Lymphotoxin alpha is a member of the tumor necrosis factor family and is a cytokine produced by lymphocytes.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MCL1 is BCL2 family apoptosis regulator, whose alternative splicing can either inhibit or promote apoptosis.
MIC2 or CD99 is expressed on all leukocytes and may augment T-cell adhesion.
C-X-C motif chemokine ligand 9 is involved in immune cell differentiation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MMP2 is a matrix metalloproteinase involved in the breakdown of extracellular matrix.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Mucin 2 coats the epithelia of mucus-membrane containing organs.
Nuclear factor kappa B subunit 1 is a part of a protein complex that controls DNA transcription and regulates immune response to infection.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Y-box binding protein 1 is target in cancer therapy, since it supports the replication of adenovirus oncolytic viruses.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: Kallikrein related peptidase 7 is a serine protease, whose overexpression may be a route for metastasis in solid tumors.
Prostaglandin E receptor 2 is a GPCR, which can regulate G protein cell signaling pathways. Functions in neutrophils modulate TNFa and IL6 production.
Prostaglandin E receptor 4 is one of the receptors for prostaglandin E2 and can activate T-cell factor signaling.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: NS1 or protein tyrosine phosphatase, non-receptor type 11 is a signaling molecule that regulates many cellular processes.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: RB or RB transcriptional corepressor 1 is a negative regulator of the cell cycle and was the first tumor suppressor gene found.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: ROBO1 or roundabout guidance receptor 1 is a member of the immunoglobulin gene superfamily.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: CCL2 or C-C motif chemokine ligand 2 binds chemokine receptors CCR2 and CCR4 with chemotactic activity on monocytes and basophils.

CD162 or selectin P ligand is a glycoprotein that functions as a high affinity counter-receptor for the cell adhesion molecules P-, E- and L- selectin expressed on myeloid cells and stimulated T lymphocytes.
Transforming growth factor beta 3 is a secreted ligand in the TGF-beta superfamily of proteins.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TK1 or thymidine kinase 1 catalyzes the addition of a gamma-phosphate group to thymidine.
CD281 or Toll-like receptor 1 is a member of Toll-like receptor family and plays a role in pathogen recognition and activation of innate immunity.
TNFRSF1A is a TNF receptor superfamily member. It plays a role in cell survival, apoptosis, and survival.
TNFR2 is a TNF receptor superfamily member 1B. It mediates the recruitment of anti-apoptotic proteins.
Tryptophan hydroxylase 1 catalyzes the first and rate limiting step in the biosynthesis of serotonin.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TTK protein kinase is a dual specificity kinase found to be a critical mitotic checkpoint protein for the segregation of chromosomes.

Pathway: Metabolism of amino acids and derivatives
Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TYRP1 or tyrosinase related protein 1 plays a role in melanin biosynthesis.
TNFSF11 is TNF superfamily member, and shown to be a dendritic cell survival factor and involved in the regulation of T cell-dependent immune response.
TNFRSF12 is TNF receptor superfamily member, and may regulate lymphocyte homeostasis.
TNFSF13 is TNF superfamily member, and is important for B cell development.
TNFRSF11A is TNF receptor superfamily member, and regulate the interaction between T cells and dendritic cells.
TNFRSF10B is TNF receptor superfamily member, and transduces apoptosis.
TNFRSF10A is TNF receptor superfamily member, and induces apoptosis.
Interleukin 18 receptor 1 is induced by IFN-alpha and IL12 in NK and T cells.
Histone deacetylase 3 removes the acetyl groups from histones to play a role in transcriptional regulation, cell cycle, and development.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: LMP1 or PDZ and LIM domain 7 functions in protein-protein recognition.
AIM2 or absent in melanoma 2 is downstream of IFN-gamma and may control cell proliferation.
IL27R or interleukin 27 receptor subunit alpha leads to transcriptional activation of STAT1 and augments the induction of T-bet expression during initiation of Th1 cell differentiation.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: ISG15 or ISG15 ubiquitin-like modifier is a ubiquitin-like protein that may regulate chemotactic activity towards neutrophils.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: VGLL4 or vestigial like family member 4 is a transcriptional cofactor that interacts with TEA domain transcription factors and lower expression correlates with poor survival in solid cancers.
Histone deacetylase 6 removes the acetyl groups from histones to play a role in transcriptional regulation, cell cycle, and development.
KLRG1 or killer cell lectin like receptor G1 is preferentially expressed on NK cells and may be regulated by MHC class I molecules.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: TRAIP or TRAF interacting protein negatively regulates innate immune signaling by inhibiting TRAF2 activation of NFKB signaling.
TNFSF13B or TNF superfamily member 13b is a TNF superfamily member and acts as a B cell activator.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: DLL3 or delta like canonical Notch ligand 3 is a Notch ligand being targeted in lung cancer.
HPSE or heparanase cleaves heparan sulfate proteoglycans to permit cell movement through extracellular matrix.
CHEK2 or checkpoint kinase 2 halts cell cycle progression in response to DNA damage and replication blocks.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: DKK1 or dickkopf WNT signaling pathway inhibitor 1 is a negative regulator of the Wnt pathway and plays a role in development.
BRD4 or bromodomain containing 4 associates with the chromosomes during mitosis.
SIGLEC9 or sialic acid binding Ig like lectin 9 has been found to be overexpressed in CD8 T cells in melanoma and may be suppress T-cell function.
CLEC2D or C-type lectin domain family 2 member D is a member of the natural killer cell receptor C-type lectin family.
IL19 or interleukin 19 belongs to the IL10 cytokine subfamily, and is preferentially expressed on monocytes.
TNFRSF12A or TNF receptor superfamily member 12A is a TNF receptor superfamily member with roles in apoptosis, angiogenesis, cell adhesion and innate immune system.
PCDH18 or protocadherin 18 is a protocadherin thought to play a role in cell-specific connections in the brain.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: RNF43 or ring finger protein 43 is a RING-type E3 ubiquitin ligase and is thought to negatively regulate Wnt signaling.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: GPRC5D or G protein-coupled receptor class C group 5 member D is a GPCR that has been a target for CAR T cells for multiple myeloma.
Histone deacetylase 8 removes the acetyl groups from histones to play a role in transcriptional regulation, cell cycle, and development.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: NECTIN4 or nectin cell adhesion molecule 4 is involved in cell adhesion.

Therapy Type: Targeted by Other Immuno-Oncology Therapy Type
Description: MOSPD2 or motile sperm domain containing 2 promotes migration of primary monocytes and neutrophils in response to chemokines.
SIGLEC15 or sialic acid binding Ig like lectin 15 binds sialylated glycoproteins and plays a role in the innate immune system.
ILDR2 negatively regulates Notch signaling and T-cell activation.
